02:27.439 --> 02:30.316
TERRY WENTZ: You go out in
the field and you look up in the sky

02:30.400 --> 02:31.651
and you see the stars,

02:31.735 --> 02:35.571
and some of that light
that's coming down to your eye

02:35.656 --> 02:38.574
has been traveling for millions of years.

02:39.034 --> 02:41.077
So you look up
and you're looking at the past,

02:41.245 --> 02:43.246
and then you look down,

02:43.497 --> 02:45.289
and you're looking at the past.

02:46.333 --> 02:49.669
You know, those dinosaur bones
are millions of years old,

02:50.045 --> 02:52.588
and that light left there, maybe
at the same time that you're looking.

02:52.673 --> 02:55.341
lt's just you're kind of
sandwiched in that world,

02:55.425 --> 02:58.928
and it's really... Really a wonderful
place being out in a field.

03:09.273 --> 03:11.482
LOUlE PSlHOYOS:
lt was a brilliant story,

03:11.567 --> 03:15.611
l mean, if you didn't have to live it
like the Larsons did.

03:20.951 --> 03:22.326
lt's a good American tale.

03:22.411 --> 03:28.457
Unfortunately, it had a bad ending
for a couple of real brilliant paleontologists.

04:14.004 --> 04:16.339
PETER LARSON:
What does that white line mean, Susan?

04:16.423 --> 04:18.507
(WlND BLOWlNG)

04:25.641 --> 04:30.186
PETER: We'd been digging at
the Ruth Mason Quarry since 1979.

04:31.063 --> 04:35.441
The 1990 season,
I think we were into the third month.

04:39.196 --> 04:40.947
We'd been working north...

04:41.031 --> 04:43.240
Actually not working
at the quarry itself anymore.

04:43.325 --> 04:45.868
We were actually prospecting
and looking for fossils.

04:45.953 --> 04:47.662
We were looking for fossils
on Sharky Williams'

04:47.746 --> 04:51.290
and his brother Maurice Williams' ranch,

04:51.375 --> 04:53.417
and finding some pretty cool stuff.

04:53.543 --> 04:57.797
And we get up on August 1 2th,
look outside the tent, and it's foggy.

04:57.881 --> 05:01.050
lt's kind of a weird thing
to have fog on the prairie.

05:01.134 --> 05:03.302
So we got a little bit later start.

05:03.387 --> 05:05.888
We weren't in any big hurry
because you couldn't see very well,

05:05.973 --> 05:09.266
and then went out to
start loading up the Suburban.

05:09.393 --> 05:11.811
We have a 1 975 Suburban, all rusted out.

05:12.062 --> 05:15.982
And l look and the tire's flat.
(CHUCKLES)

05:16.066 --> 05:19.610
So l say, "Oh, crap." Well, almost flat.
Still had a little bit of air in it.

05:19.736 --> 05:23.906
So l go in the back to get the spare tire,

05:23.991 --> 05:25.950
and the spare tire's flat.

05:26.034 --> 05:28.494
So l pull out the tire pump,

05:28.704 --> 05:31.080
and the tire pump hose is broken.

05:31.248 --> 05:33.666
So we figure,
"l guess we better...

05:33.750 --> 05:35.001
"We better head into town

05:35.085 --> 05:36.961
"while we still have enough
air in the tire to get there."

05:37.087 --> 05:38.713
WENTZ: We decided,
"Well, we're gonna have to go to town."

05:38.797 --> 05:40.840
You know, l'd been out there
for four or five weeks.

05:40.924 --> 05:44.510
Going to town, that's okay.
l can take it easy for half an hour, an hour.

05:44.594 --> 05:47.221
That's fine with me, but, of course, Susan...

05:48.098 --> 05:52.101
Susan just can't handle that.
You know, that's a waste of time, right?

05:52.352 --> 05:54.353
SUSAN HENDRlCKSON:
There was the flat tire. l said, "Great.

05:54.438 --> 05:58.315
"You guys go to town. You don't need me.
l've got this place l want to look at."

05:59.443 --> 06:02.695
Out there, you need landmarks
to find your way around.

06:02.863 --> 06:07.116
And I said, "Okay, it's foggy. You can't see.
Make sure you don't walk in a circle."

06:07.576 --> 06:09.952
And two hours later,
l was right back where l started,

06:10.287 --> 06:11.954
and l could not believe it.

06:12.039 --> 06:15.416
l just couldn't believe it 'cause l was,
like, trying so hard to walk straight.

06:15.500 --> 06:16.667
lt was like...

06:16.752 --> 06:18.210
l felt really stupid.

06:20.213 --> 06:22.798
l believe it was the next day when
we went back with the video camera

06:22.883 --> 06:26.802
and just kind of reenacted,
you know, how l found her.

06:28.138 --> 06:30.222
Anybody who had any idea

06:30.307 --> 06:33.559
of what a fossil versus a rock was
would have seen it

06:33.643 --> 06:36.896
'cause there was
a lot of broken bones dribbling down.

06:37.064 --> 06:41.150
About eight foot up the side of the cliff,
there were three articulated vertebrae

06:41.276 --> 06:43.486
and a couple of other pieces
of bone sticking out.

06:43.612 --> 06:46.530
From the debris pile, l picked up scraps

06:47.157 --> 06:49.366
that showed the hollowness
and took it with,

06:49.576 --> 06:51.911
'cause l knew if l went back
to where they were working,

06:51.995 --> 06:53.996
they wouldn't believe me.

06:54.331 --> 06:57.458
We got back after fixing the tire
and we were at the dig site.

06:57.542 --> 07:01.170
We were just finishing up doing stuff,
and Susan comes up.

07:01.379 --> 07:03.255
And she opens her hand,

07:03.340 --> 07:07.343
and she's got
two pretty small pieces of bone,

07:07.427 --> 07:09.553
only about this big, in her hand.

07:09.805 --> 07:12.932
And l'd never seen the inside
of a T. rex vertebra before,

07:13.016 --> 07:16.268
but l knew exactly that was
what she had in her hand,

07:16.353 --> 07:19.522
and l says, "ls there more of it?"
She said, "There's a lot more."

07:19.606 --> 07:21.899
So we ran, literally ran back to the site.

07:22.025 --> 07:24.652
(MUSlC PLAYlNG)

07:32.035 --> 07:35.704
PETER: l crawl up on the cliff face
and l see three articulated vertebrae,

07:36.081 --> 07:37.414
and from that point on,

07:37.499 --> 07:41.418
l'm absolutely certain this is gonna be
the best thing we ever found

07:41.503 --> 07:43.170
and it's gonna be a complete T. rex.

07:43.380 --> 07:45.005
NEAL LARSON: He called up and said,

07:45.090 --> 07:48.384
"Neal, l need you to bring
a lot of plaster two-by-fours."

07:49.010 --> 07:50.594
Well, it took me a day
to get everything ready,

07:50.679 --> 07:52.972
and l came up, and l got up
there with all these materials,

07:53.056 --> 07:55.975
and he took me over to this big cliff,

07:56.059 --> 07:58.018
and he said, "Take a look."

07:58.145 --> 07:59.478
And l looked at it, and l looked at him.

07:59.563 --> 08:02.940
l said, "ls that T. rex?" He said, "Yes,

08:03.233 --> 08:05.484
"and l think it's all here."

08:10.407 --> 08:12.867
And we haven't started digging
or haven't moved anything around yet.

08:12.951 --> 08:15.494
We've just been looking at it
and taking some pictures

08:15.579 --> 08:17.705
and trying to figure out how to proceed.

08:17.789 --> 08:20.958
There's a real mass of bones here.
Some are caught up in concretion,

08:21.084 --> 08:24.128
but most appear to be
really excellently preserved.

08:24.546 --> 08:28.924
And l believe that the tail's going that way
and the skull is going this way,

08:30.051 --> 08:32.219
but we're just gonna
have to dig it up and see.

08:32.929 --> 08:35.556
PETER: Collecting fossils
is something that's very timely.

08:35.640 --> 08:38.683
Fossils are discovered
because they're weathering out,

08:38.768 --> 08:40.936
because the forces of nature,

08:41.020 --> 08:45.024
rain, winds, freezing,
thawing, even snowfall,

08:45.108 --> 08:46.609
have an effect on that fossil.

08:46.693 --> 08:50.571
Every day that it's outside
is a day that it's going to destruction.

08:53.909 --> 08:58.162
NEAL: We started by picking up
all these thousands of fragments of bones

08:58.246 --> 09:00.623
and bagging them and labeling them.

09:02.667 --> 09:05.669
WENTZ: Well, the plan of attack
is to protect the specimen, first of all,

09:05.754 --> 09:08.672
and then you go above the specimen
and dig down to it,

09:08.798 --> 09:12.927
so that you can get all the way around it
to remove it from the cliff.

09:19.559 --> 09:22.770
PETER: We basically used these
ditch-digging tools, picks and shovels,

09:22.854 --> 09:24.438
to dig down that 30 feet

09:24.522 --> 09:28.984
from where l thought
we could get back into the cliff face

09:29.152 --> 09:33.197
far enough to uncover what l thought
would be the limits of that skeleton.

09:36.993 --> 09:39.828
NEAL: Probably the hardest work
l've ever had to do in my life.

09:39.913 --> 09:45.376
We were doing this all in temperatures
around 1 1 5 degrees every day.

09:49.297 --> 09:50.422
PETER: lt was very hard work

09:50.507 --> 09:54.969
but it was very easy
to put in a lot of energy into it

09:55.053 --> 09:58.514
because we all wanted to see
what the skeleton was going to look like.

10:00.809 --> 10:04.311
WENTZ: Basically, we'd take different
sections, so we weren't in each other's way,

10:04.396 --> 10:08.524
and just kind of worked the specimen
until we could start removing bones.

10:11.695 --> 10:14.280
HENDRlCKSON: You know, and every time
somebody found a bone or a fragment,

10:14.364 --> 10:15.656
theyjust said, "The 'S' bone."

10:15.740 --> 10:18.200
We wouldn't say, "Skull."
We didn't want to jinx it.

10:20.120 --> 10:21.787
PETER: Pretty early on,

10:21.871 --> 10:25.165
l hit something hard, and so l stopped.
(LAUGHS)

10:28.003 --> 10:30.045
"lt's the 'S' word," l said,

10:30.422 --> 10:32.172
thinking, "l bet l hit the skull."

10:40.390 --> 10:41.640
When l got down digging,

10:41.725 --> 10:44.351
and then started really
working with the smaller knife,

10:44.436 --> 10:46.353
we found, as we were going down,

10:46.438 --> 10:47.896
is the back of the skull.

10:50.317 --> 10:53.944
And we're getting down
and here's this skull taking shape,

10:54.029 --> 10:55.529
and we get out on the side,

10:55.613 --> 10:57.990
and l put Terry to work
on cleaning the side of the skull

10:58.074 --> 11:00.784
'cause he's really our best preparator.

11:01.703 --> 11:05.414
WENTZ: Pete let me work on part of the skull
in the field, which was amazing.

11:08.251 --> 11:12.254
PETER: He's working and uncovering
the teeth one by one by one.

11:15.467 --> 11:17.843
NEAL: lt was spectacular.

11:17.927 --> 11:22.431
Teeth like this
just sticking right out of the skull.

11:22.599 --> 11:26.060
We're going, "Oh, my God.
Look at this thing. Look how huge it is.

11:26.144 --> 11:28.187
"This has gotta be bigger than the one
at the American Museum.

11:28.271 --> 11:30.189
"lt's huge. lt's wonderful."

11:41.034 --> 11:44.828
We had started a long time ago
naming particular dinosaurs,

11:44.913 --> 11:49.041
and the name Sue, for Susan Hendrickson,
goes down in history,

11:49.125 --> 11:50.542
and l think that's kind of a cool way

11:50.627 --> 11:54.129
to reward those amateurs
who make these discoveries.

12:02.180 --> 12:05.724
WENTZ: We were all experienced diggers.
You know, it was just a total focused effort.

12:05.809 --> 12:10.687
We would just work into the specimen,
remove things that we could,

12:10.772 --> 12:11.980
protect the rest of it,

12:12.065 --> 12:15.567
and then take it out of the ground
and get it back into the laboratory,

12:15.735 --> 12:17.820
where you can have
a more controlled environment

12:17.904 --> 12:19.905
to take care of the specimen.

12:19.989 --> 12:22.116
NEAL:
The amount of new things that we found

12:22.200 --> 12:23.617
and the amount of scientific information

12:23.701 --> 12:26.870
that we discovered while finding Sue
was enormous.

12:27.122 --> 12:29.248
PETER:
Beautifully preserved, articulated skull,

12:29.332 --> 12:32.084
articulated vertebral column up to the pelvis

12:32.168 --> 12:34.753
with the tail and shoulder blade
and all this stuff,

12:34.838 --> 12:37.131
and it's just like, "Holy cow."
And wonderful preservation.

12:37.215 --> 12:42.428
Just fantastic bones that were...
Just beautiful surface on them.

12:47.684 --> 12:49.768
NEAL:
Every time we were ready to take a bone out

12:49.853 --> 12:51.270
or every time there was some new discovery,

12:51.354 --> 12:53.063
Pete would take this butcher paper out,

12:53.148 --> 12:55.858
and he mapped each and every bone,
one on one,

12:55.942 --> 12:57.484
that we found that was excavated.

13:26.764 --> 13:29.475
NEAL: Pete and l had quite
a few discussions, "What would be fair?"

13:29.559 --> 13:33.187
$5,000 is the most that anybody
had ever given anyone for a dinosaur,

13:33.313 --> 13:35.606
for any fossil in the ground.

13:35.732 --> 13:37.065
So Pete wrote a check out for him

13:37.150 --> 13:39.776
and a contract
that he wanted Maurice to sign.

13:39.903 --> 13:42.154
l showed it to him, and he said,
"We don't need to sign anything.

13:42.238 --> 13:44.406
"This is something...
A handshake between friends,

13:44.741 --> 13:47.242
"and the $5,000 is fine. I'm happy with that."

13:47.327 --> 13:49.953
And, you know, that was the most
that any landowner had ever gotten.

13:50.038 --> 13:54.374
We shook hands, and he was pretty excited
about seeing it set up in the museum.

13:59.672 --> 14:02.257
(lNDlSTlNCT CHATTER)

14:04.802 --> 14:08.138
Last phase of getting Sue out of the ground

14:08.223 --> 14:13.352
we used, basically, Egyptian techniques
to get this large block.

14:13.603 --> 14:18.732
l mean, one of the blocks weighed
probably something close to 10,000 pounds.

14:18.942 --> 14:22.528
There was probably about 10 ton
of material, total, that we had to load up.

14:31.287 --> 14:34.831
NEAL: Once we had the skull and pelvic block
and the tail vertebrae and everything else,

14:34.916 --> 14:37.626
we knew we could haul
a lot of the stuff on our Bobcat trailer.

14:37.752 --> 14:40.379
We had no idea how we were going to
be able to get all these other things.

14:40.463 --> 14:45.425
My brother John had built
a tandem-axle trailer earlier that year.

14:45.593 --> 14:47.886
PETER: With that and the other
pickup truck that we had there,

14:47.971 --> 14:51.682
we were able to load the fossil up.

14:53.393 --> 14:56.478
After we had built pallets
underneath the fossil,

14:56.604 --> 14:58.689
we were able to scooch
some plywood underneath 'em,

14:58.773 --> 15:01.233
so that we could move it
with chains and come-alongs

15:01.317 --> 15:03.860
and get it into the trailers.

15:08.283 --> 15:12.119
lt was and still is today the most exciting,

15:12.203 --> 15:16.039
the most wonderful excavation
we have ever done,

15:16.165 --> 15:18.834
the most incredible thing
we have ever done.

16:00.376 --> 16:02.252
(BlRDS CHlRPlNG)

16:05.089 --> 16:06.340
PHlL MANNlNG:
Dinosaurs, for me, are still

16:06.424 --> 16:09.968
one of the most amazing creatures
ever to have lived on the planet.

16:10.053 --> 16:13.013
You're touching something that was alive

16:13.139 --> 16:16.224
65, 100, or three or more
hundred million years ago.

16:16.726 --> 16:18.727
When you pick up a fossil,

16:19.062 --> 16:22.564
and you're the first ever human being

16:22.732 --> 16:26.234
to touch the remains of that organism,

16:26.903 --> 16:28.528
it's a remarkable feeling.

16:29.197 --> 16:31.031
PHlLlP CURRlE:
Dinosaurs are iconic animals.

16:31.115 --> 16:33.408
They represent paleontology in general.

16:33.493 --> 16:34.493
They represent science.

16:34.577 --> 16:38.622
Dinosaurs lived for 1 50 million years,
and they dominated the world for that long,

16:38.706 --> 16:41.416
and yet humans have only been
around for three, four, or five.

16:41.834 --> 16:46.046
What are our chances? We seem to
be approaching these big problems.

16:46.130 --> 16:47.339
VlNCENT SANTUCCl:
Most of what is to be learned

16:47.423 --> 16:50.717
about the history of life
is yet to be discovered.

16:50.802 --> 16:53.053
What's still out there?
What's still in the ground?

16:53.137 --> 16:56.556
What some kids might find
1 00 years from now

16:56.641 --> 16:58.809
will contribute to
that greater understanding.

16:58.935 --> 17:01.269
PSlHOYOS: We know nothing
about the history of the planet

17:01.354 --> 17:03.522
unless learning it through a paleontologist.

17:03.606 --> 17:07.317
And it's that sense of deep time,
real deep time,

17:07.734 --> 17:11.445
that gives you a sense of who you are
and how you fit into the scheme of things.

17:11.614 --> 17:14.281
(WlND BLOWlNG)

17:18.371 --> 17:20.789
(MUSlC PLAYlNG)

17:49.527 --> 17:52.320
PETER: I first fell in love with fossils
when l was about four years old.

17:53.531 --> 17:58.827
l picked up this small tooth
down on my folks' ranch.

17:59.871 --> 18:04.332
From then on, l just was so fascinated
with fossils. l just couldn't stop.

18:04.751 --> 18:08.086
Every day that the weather was good
and every day that the weather was great

18:08.171 --> 18:09.963
that was on a weekend,
if we were going to school

18:10.047 --> 18:12.132
or in the summertime,
Dad would always say,

18:12.216 --> 18:13.383
"Let's go out rock hunting."

18:23.728 --> 18:25.771
PETER:
We ended up starting this little museum,

18:25.855 --> 18:28.690
and we'd charge the adults
in our family five cents.

18:29.358 --> 18:30.609
We had little displays

18:30.693 --> 18:32.235
where we set up the things
that we had collected.

18:32.320 --> 18:34.613
Notjust fossils and rocks,

18:34.697 --> 18:37.157
but also what we thought were antiques.

18:37.366 --> 18:41.995
We had this horrible hobby that started
to captivate every part of our life.

18:44.749 --> 18:47.918
PETER: Eventually l decided
to really get into paleontology,

18:48.127 --> 18:51.254
and so went to the South Dakota School
of Mines and Technology in Rapid City.

18:55.384 --> 18:57.719
Junior year, we went to
the Tucson Gem and Mineral Show,

18:57.804 --> 19:02.098
and really saw how specimens
are purchased by museums

19:02.183 --> 19:03.892
and purchased by private collectors.

19:06.687 --> 19:08.063
And by the time we graduated,

19:08.147 --> 19:10.065
we started this business
called Black Hills Minerals

19:10.191 --> 19:12.150
as this Earth science supply house.

19:17.156 --> 19:18.865
Eventually my younger brother Neal,

19:18.950 --> 19:20.742
who was also a student
at the School of Mines,

19:20.868 --> 19:22.744
and Bob Farrar, one of his classmates,

19:22.870 --> 19:24.746
started working with us as well.

19:25.581 --> 19:27.833
BOB FARRAR: With the three ofus
all going to the School of Mines,

19:27.917 --> 19:30.627
we were problems there because

19:30.711 --> 19:34.047
all of us chose not to go into industry.

19:35.007 --> 19:38.552
NEAL: The first year was terrible,
the second year was not so good,

19:38.636 --> 19:40.929
but it was sort of turning into a business.

19:43.432 --> 19:46.351
PETER: As we kept going,
we kept collecting more and more fossils

19:46.435 --> 19:51.940
and had the idea of, "lt probably would work
to sell these as display specimens."

19:52.608 --> 19:56.570
NEAL: ln 1978, we were going pretty strong.

19:56.654 --> 19:58.488
We were selling mostly fossils.

19:58.573 --> 20:01.408
We were going out
and doing geological exploration.

20:01.534 --> 20:04.202
PETER: So by 1979,

20:04.287 --> 20:06.204
we created this new entity

20:06.289 --> 20:09.791
called Black Hills Institute of
Geological Research Incorporated

20:10.042 --> 20:11.960
in the center of the Black Hills.

20:13.129 --> 20:15.130
(MUSlC PLAYlNG)

20:28.561 --> 20:31.271
HENDRlCKSON:
I first met Pete Larson when I was in Peru.

20:31.355 --> 20:34.149
l was down there visiting
my friend Kirby Siber,

20:34.442 --> 20:39.321
who was about to go out in the field
and collect some fossil whales and, uh...

20:40.197 --> 20:42.991
And he had asked Pete
to come down to do that,

20:43.284 --> 20:44.784
and the three of us went.

20:45.286 --> 20:47.287
(MUSlC PLAYlNG)

20:52.752 --> 20:55.420
PETER: l had known
Susan Hendrickson for about five years

20:55.504 --> 20:57.756
before she found the dinosaur Sue.

20:57.840 --> 21:02.302
And Susan was one of those volunteers
who came to work at the Ruth Mason Quarry

21:02.386 --> 21:05.931
after we had met in Peru
a number of years before.

21:06.057 --> 21:10.685
HENDRlCKSON: My attraction to him
was his expertise and his enthusiasm

21:10.770 --> 21:13.396
or passion for fossils, which l shared.

21:13.522 --> 21:16.900
Pete is one of the best
paleontologists around.

21:17.026 --> 21:20.028
There's a few other people
that might be at his level.

21:20.196 --> 21:22.781
PETER: There was some
romantic involvement at the time

21:22.865 --> 21:25.867
between Susan Hendrickson and l,
although that was pretty much over.

21:25.993 --> 21:30.372
That was sort of short-lived
and we were, at this point, just friends.

21:30.539 --> 21:34.793
And she was just having
one more season of collecting

21:34.877 --> 21:37.128
before she was moving back to Seattle.

21:37.213 --> 21:39.714
HENDRlCKSON: He had this whole
other part of him, which was the lnstitute,

21:39.799 --> 21:41.257
and he had a lot of responsibilities.

21:41.342 --> 21:42.592
And that part didn't interest me.

21:42.677 --> 21:44.844
l tried to help him, l commended him,

