expecting to seal off the building

28:08.937 --> 28:10.188
and keep anybody from going in.

28:10.272 --> 28:11.773
"Just wait here. We have to get Pete."

28:11.899 --> 28:14.275
They sent me to get Pete, and l was running.

28:14.401 --> 28:16.402
PETER:
I lived in a trailer house behind the Institute.

28:17.404 --> 28:19.906
"The FBl's here. They're all over the place."

28:20.532 --> 28:23.159
They've got yellow police tape
around the main building.

28:23.243 --> 28:26.162
NEAL:
"Do not cross. Police line. Do not cross."

28:26.372 --> 28:29.040
FARRAR: It was hard to know
what was really happening at that point.

28:29.124 --> 28:30.541
PETER: l go down to the office,

28:30.626 --> 28:32.293
and there's two FBl agents sitting there.

28:32.378 --> 28:34.087
"You've stolen this from federal land,

28:34.171 --> 28:35.838
"and we're coming here to seize this."

28:35.923 --> 28:40.218
PATRlCK DUFFY: l got a phone call from
Peter Larson because it wasn't just the FBl.

28:40.302 --> 28:42.136
lt was personnel from South Dakota Tech,

28:42.221 --> 28:44.263
it was personnel
from other federal agencies,

28:44.348 --> 28:46.724
and it was the National Guard.

28:48.477 --> 28:50.395
HARLAN:
The U.S. Attorney at the time, Kevin Schieffer,

28:50.771 --> 28:53.439
got reporters together
in the Federal Building in Rapid City

28:53.899 --> 28:56.401
and announced that
the seizure was ongoing.

28:56.485 --> 28:59.070
The purpose of our action this morning

28:59.238 --> 29:03.366
is to preserve. . .

29:03.450 --> 29:07.036
The scientific knowledge
and integrity of these fossils.

29:07.287 --> 29:10.581
Then, of course, the entire press corps
hopped in their cars,

29:10.999 --> 29:13.167
and we drove to Hill City.

29:15.838 --> 29:18.381
NEAL: They were supposed to
take things related to Sue,

29:18.507 --> 29:19.632
but they took everything.

29:19.716 --> 29:23.886
They went through all of our offices,
all of our desks, all of our mail trays,

29:23.971 --> 29:25.972
taking mail opened, unopened.

29:26.056 --> 29:27.181
WENTZ: Somebody called me and said,

29:27.266 --> 29:30.768
"The FBl's got crime scene tape around
the Institute, and they're taking Sue."

29:30.853 --> 29:33.646
l hung up the phone, and l went
as fast as I could down to the Institute.

29:33.730 --> 29:36.649
l don't know how many agents they had,
30-some people or whatever.

29:36.733 --> 29:37.942
lt was just insane.

29:38.026 --> 29:40.695
I didn't even think about it.
l grabbed the tape and l go under it.

29:40.779 --> 29:43.448
l just went to the specimen.
That was my concern.

29:43.532 --> 29:44.866
l could just see these idiots,

29:45.576 --> 29:49.203
you know, just try to pack up
my dinosaur and take it away and ruin it.

29:49.288 --> 29:53.207
How dare they?
How dare these people do this?

29:53.292 --> 29:56.252
Unconscionable. l can't imagine
somebody being able to do this

29:56.336 --> 29:58.629
here in the United States of America,
in a free country.

30:01.717 --> 30:07.305
ln order to ensure that this dinosaur
could be carefully packed up, we helped.

30:07.890 --> 30:11.100
lt was pretty clear that they didn't know
what they were doing.

30:11.268 --> 30:12.768
WENTZ: These people didn't know anything.

30:12.853 --> 30:15.438
l mean, most of these guys
hardly go out in the field at all.

30:15.522 --> 30:18.900
What do they know about preparing a fossil
or packing it or anything?

30:18.984 --> 30:22.195
The Larsons were trying to do
a little bit of negotiating.

30:22.279 --> 30:26.574
"Put Sue under lock and key
at our place to prevent damage."

30:26.742 --> 30:28.159
l said to Kevin Schieffer,

30:28.243 --> 30:31.370
"You just tell me,
and that fossil won't go anywhere.

30:31.455 --> 30:33.623
"lt's not like it's going
to disappear in a briefcase."

30:33.832 --> 30:36.417
That request was denied.

30:36.585 --> 30:39.837
lt is clearly a violation
under the Antiquities Act

30:39.922 --> 30:45.468
to remove antiquities
from United States lands

30:45.594 --> 30:47.345
without the permission of the United States.

30:47.596 --> 30:49.972
The federal government doesn't
show up with the National Guard

30:51.350 --> 30:52.683
and an Assistant or. . .
Pardon me,

30:52.768 --> 30:55.144
an Acting United States Attorney
in pancake makeup. . .

30:56.522 --> 31:00.858
. . .with the intention of working things out
somewhere down the road.

31:10.410 --> 31:13.538
PETER: After we got over the initial shock,

31:13.747 --> 31:15.790
those of us who were packing the dinosaur

31:15.874 --> 31:18.751
kind of went into our packing mode,

31:18.835 --> 31:20.378
but towards the end of the day,

31:20.462 --> 31:24.340
it became obvious that something
was going on with the town.

31:24.508 --> 31:25.967
NEAL: People around town noticed.

31:26.093 --> 31:29.387
They noticed all the cop cars.
They noticed the police tape.

31:29.471 --> 31:32.056
PETER: All of a sudden,
there were people with signs

31:32.140 --> 31:33.516
out in front of our building.

31:33.642 --> 31:36.644
lt was clear that people were not
happy with what was going on.

31:36.812 --> 31:40.773
The protest developed very quickly,
so there were a lot of people on the street.

31:40.857 --> 31:42.942
PSlHOYOS:
l was working for National Geographic,

31:43.026 --> 31:45.319
and we were gonna take the skull of Sue

31:45.404 --> 31:47.863
and put it into a CAT scan
of what they use for the space shuttles

31:47.948 --> 31:50.366
to see if we could
see inside the skull of Sue.

31:50.576 --> 31:53.327
And Terry Wentz answered the phone

31:53.453 --> 31:55.162
and he said, "Well, l don't think so."

31:55.247 --> 31:59.500
So I got on the next plane I could,
and the place was surrounded by cops.

31:59.668 --> 32:02.753
l mean, you thought that there was
a real T . rex loose on the property.

32:04.298 --> 32:09.260
PETER: The next day in, they brought in
reinforcements, a lot more people.

32:10.053 --> 32:12.513
HAROLD SYKORA: The idea was
that we were going to load this stuff up

32:12.681 --> 32:15.141
and haul it somewhere.

32:15.225 --> 32:20.104
And when the Director of Military Support,
one of the colonels, got down there,

32:20.188 --> 32:21.647
he called and said,

32:21.732 --> 32:25.401
"Hey, General, this is not what we expected.
This is a media event.

32:25.736 --> 32:27.737
"We got school kids out here.

32:27.821 --> 32:30.698
"We got parents out here.
What should we do?"

32:30.782 --> 32:32.825
And l said, "Well, just go do it."

32:33.368 --> 32:36.287
PROTESTORS:
Save Sue! Don't be cruel ! Save Sue!

32:36.413 --> 32:44.629
Don't be cruel ! Save Sue!

32:44.796 --> 32:51.010
Save Sue! Save Sue!

32:51.094 --> 32:55.097
All day long, the protestors kept arriving.

32:55.349 --> 32:57.266
Protesting about what
the government was doing.

32:57.517 --> 32:59.143
PROTESTORS: (CHANTlNG)
Save Sue! Save Sue!

32:59.227 --> 33:02.355
Save Sue! Save Sue! Save Sue!

33:02.522 --> 33:26.796
Shame on you !

33:26.922 --> 33:29.173
Shame on you ! Shame on you !

33:29.257 --> 33:30.841
(CHANTlNG FADES)

33:30.926 --> 33:33.511
PSlHOYOS:
Kids protesting, adults protesting.

33:33.637 --> 33:36.764
lt was not the sort of public-relations event

33:37.182 --> 33:38.766
that, you know, law enforcement likes

33:38.850 --> 33:41.435
because they're taking away this T . rex

33:41.645 --> 33:43.604
from a very small town
that really could use it.

33:50.278 --> 33:51.529
PETER: On the third day,

33:51.613 --> 33:55.449
the National Guard had brought up

33:55.534 --> 33:57.535
large equipment,
including forklifts and things,

33:57.619 --> 34:00.037
and the crowd had grown by this time.

34:00.455 --> 34:01.914
Leave our Sue!

34:01.998 --> 34:04.333
Leave our Sue! Leave our Sue!

34:04.418 --> 34:07.044
PETER: People were so emotionally involved.

34:07.462 --> 34:10.715
MARlON ZENKER:
The amazing thing, to me, wasn't just us.

34:10.799 --> 34:12.132
The whole town...

34:12.801 --> 34:15.136
The entire town of Hill City

34:15.512 --> 34:18.806
was in mourning
when they took that dinosaur away.

34:18.974 --> 34:21.641
(OVERLAPPlNG CHATTER AND CHANTlNG)

34:25.522 --> 34:27.481
PETER: Here was a dream that the town had.

34:27.607 --> 34:29.984
lt was our dinosaur.

34:30.068 --> 34:34.321
lt was our museum. lt was our lives

34:34.406 --> 34:37.241
that had been just torn to pieces.

34:38.076 --> 34:40.369
HENDRlCKSON:
l was in France when they called me.

34:40.454 --> 34:43.330
And, you know, l thought it was a joke.

34:43.831 --> 34:46.500
Couldn't believe it, and l cried.

34:50.130 --> 34:52.005
WENTZ: l was highly emotional,

34:52.340 --> 34:55.134
but from that moment that l heard
that the specimen was going to be taken,

34:55.302 --> 34:57.094
my focus was on the specimen.

34:57.179 --> 34:59.764
Legally and all that other crap,

35:00.140 --> 35:01.849
that's not my concern.

35:02.184 --> 35:05.311
My concern was make sure
that dinosaur was going to transport,

35:05.395 --> 35:06.687
everything was going to be safe.

35:06.855 --> 35:08.814
There's my. . . My, uh. . .

35:09.232 --> 35:11.901
. . .three children that were here also.

35:12.027 --> 35:14.862
That was very hard for them to understand.

35:15.489 --> 35:19.283
l couldn't explain it to them.

35:19.493 --> 35:24.622
Sue belonged here,
and what happened was not right.

35:24.956 --> 35:27.208
(FORKLlFT BEEPlNG)

35:39.304 --> 35:42.973
HOCHSTAFL: You know, it was like
a funeral, losing a family member.

35:43.433 --> 35:44.892
lt just felt like a nightmare,

35:45.060 --> 35:47.895
like it just wasn't really happening. Just. . .

35:48.688 --> 35:50.272
The place was a mess.

35:50.357 --> 35:52.691
We, all of a sudden, were a mess.

35:54.069 --> 35:55.736
And they hauled Sue away.

36:09.209 --> 36:11.877
ZENKER: I don't know how Peter did it.

36:14.589 --> 36:19.385
One of the hardest things to watch
and be a part of

36:21.471 --> 36:26.058
was knowing that, literally,
Peter was in love with that dinosaur.

36:44.244 --> 36:50.374
(WOMAN SlNGlNG)

36:52.294 --> 36:54.753
(MUSlC PLAYlNG)

37:52.896 --> 37:55.272
KRlSTlN DONNAN:
I grew up in Hill City,

37:55.440 --> 37:58.943
and l lived in Los Angeles
at the time Sue was discovered.

37:59.027 --> 38:02.488
ln 1 992, l was working
at Unsolved Mysteries,

38:02.614 --> 38:04.198
a TV show on NBC,

38:04.282 --> 38:07.034
researching cases
where people convicted of crimes

38:07.118 --> 38:08.661
insist they were innocent.

38:08.787 --> 38:11.121
And that first day the dinosaur was seized,

38:11.206 --> 38:13.749
Pete called me on the phone
in the middle of it all.

38:13.959 --> 38:19.421
He said the FBl was here,
and it was dramatic and scary,

38:19.547 --> 38:23.550
and he needed coverage,
he needed support.

38:23.969 --> 38:28.055
So l thought, "Well, l'll go cover the story
and take a hiatus

38:28.223 --> 38:30.766
"and maybe move away from LA forever."

38:30.892 --> 38:35.270
l didn't know, but l just packed up
and bailed back to South Dakota

38:35.397 --> 38:38.315
by the end of the year to cover the story
and see what was gonna happen to it.

38:38.400 --> 38:40.192
(THEME SONG PLAYlNG)

38:41.194 --> 38:43.487
America's lndian tribes
have fought the white man

38:43.571 --> 38:45.739
over many different issues
through the years,

38:45.824 --> 38:48.450
but the newest fight is over a dinosaur.

38:53.248 --> 38:56.166
HARLAN:
lt was a big story and a very unusual story.

38:56.459 --> 39:00.379
To have the federal government
come in and seize Sue,

39:00.505 --> 39:01.588
everything exploded.

39:01.756 --> 39:02.715
Controversy tonight. . .

39:02.799 --> 39:05.551
Controversy surrounding the lnstitute
and their most famous discovery.

39:05.635 --> 39:07.761
lt may be the custody battle of the century.

39:07.846 --> 39:09.722
Scientists, lndians, the U.S. government. . .

39:09.848 --> 39:13.017
You find any fossils,
the government may take them away.

39:13.101 --> 39:16.520
Not only has he taken this dinosaur away,
but he's taken our research away, too,

39:16.604 --> 39:19.398
every photograph,
every record we had about this dinosaur

39:19.524 --> 39:20.983
and the locality where she was found.

39:21.151 --> 39:23.277
Sue was seized pursuant
to a search warrant,

39:23.778 --> 39:25.487
but there was never a crime charged.

39:25.655 --> 39:29.158
Pat and l talked about filing suit.

39:29.284 --> 39:31.452
We sued the federal government
for return of our property.

39:34.789 --> 39:38.459
The Black Hills lnstitute said it purchased
the fossil from Maurice Williams.

39:38.710 --> 39:43.505
Originally Maurice Williams said that, too,
but then he changed his claim,

39:43.631 --> 39:47.634
and he said he had not
sold the fossil and that he owned it.

39:48.053 --> 39:49.803
Mr. Williams. . .

39:49.971 --> 39:54.558
HARLAN: Pete and Neal had made a deal
with Maurice Williams for $5,000.

39:54.642 --> 39:57.561
NEAL: On that Saturday, the day before
we finished getting Sue out of the ground,

39:57.645 --> 40:01.440
we gave Maurice Williams a check for $5,000

40:01.566 --> 40:03.984
that said, "For Theropod Sue,"
on the bottom of the check.

40:04.069 --> 40:06.528
PETER:
Even though $5,000 may not seem like a lot,

40:06.654 --> 40:09.239
it was a lot of money
for our company to spend,

40:09.491 --> 40:13.535
and no one had ever paid that much
for an undiscovered fossil before.

40:14.329 --> 40:17.206
We had lots of conversations
with Maurice Williams

40:17.290 --> 40:18.749
about what was happening to the dinosaur.

40:18.833 --> 40:21.293
He knew that we were going to
bring it back to Hill City.

40:21.377 --> 40:23.170
He was completely in favor of that.

40:23.254 --> 40:24.922
He knew about the museum
we were building.

40:25.006 --> 40:27.049
He knew we were going
to be preparing the fossil.

40:27.175 --> 40:28.884
MAN: That's about the only ones that we have.

40:33.431 --> 40:34.723
(LAUGHTER)

40:34.808 --> 40:36.058
HENDRlCKSON: Well, it's not the only one.

40:36.142 --> 40:37.434
-Almost.
-Almost.

40:37.519 --> 40:39.353
And it's not. . . Not completely. . .

40:43.024 --> 40:45.484
(LAUGHTER)

40:53.618 --> 40:56.411
HARLAN: l had known people
who knew Maurice and Sharky,

40:56.496 --> 41:00.124
and they were colorful
and controversial figures in their own right

41:00.375 --> 41:01.834
on the Cheyenne River Reservation.

41:01.960 --> 41:04.795
Numerous people said,
"Had we known you were on his ranch,

41:04.879 --> 41:05.879
"we would have warned you."

41:14.848 --> 41:17.391
There began to emerge some controversy

41:17.475 --> 41:22.688
about Sue being collected from lndian land
and the ownership issue.

41:42.750 --> 41:45.752
DUFFY:
You could not have discovered this rex

41:46.880 --> 41:51.925
in a worse and potentially
legally complicated place.

41:56.222 --> 41:59.558
It was discovered
within the exterior boundaries

41:59.642 --> 42:01.768
of the Cheyenne River Sioux tribe

42:01.853 --> 42:05.772
on land which was held in trust

42:05.940 --> 42:08.525
for the benefit of Maurice Williams,
the landowner.

42:08.610 --> 42:10.152
lt wasn't tribal land,

42:10.403 --> 42:11.820
it wasn't federal land,

42:11.946 --> 42:14.489
it was a really. . .

42:15.116 --> 42:19.620
Sue came out from
an absolute legal netherworld.

42:23.791 --> 42:26.043
BRUCE ELLlSON:
lndian people were given...

42:26.127 --> 42:29.129
Heads of household were given 1 60 acres

42:29.756 --> 42:32.090
in what we call the Allotment Acts.

42:32.342 --> 42:33.550
And that was to try

42:33.635 --> 42:36.637
and make people
who didn't understand land ownership

42:36.721 --> 42:39.431
be owners of land,
but they really didn't own the land.

42:39.515 --> 42:43.227
So there became this concept
of trust responsibility,

42:43.853 --> 42:47.356
and nothing ostensibly is
supposed to happen to that land

42:47.440 --> 42:49.566
without the approval
of the federal government

42:49.651 --> 42:50.734
through the Bureau of lndian Affairs.

42:53.321 --> 42:55.072
CARSON MURDY: On the reservations,

42:55.156 --> 43:00.827
the United States holds that land in trust
for the individual lndian as the beneficiary.

43:01.079 --> 43:06.166
And the United States
has a fiduciary responsibility

43:06.251 --> 43:09.169
to individual lndians and/or their families

43:09.379 --> 43:11.505
that they get the highest
and best use out of it.

43:14.926 --> 43:20.389
DUFFY: All across the west, it is
a patchwork quilt of laws and regulations

43:20.473 --> 43:25.060
concerning what can and can't be
harvested that's paleontological.

43:27.981 --> 43:30.565
You can be all right in this quarter section,

43:30.650 --> 43:32.067
but if you get off a little bit. . .

43:32.151 --> 43:34.069
Remember, this is before GPS.

43:34.487 --> 43:36.280
lf you get off a little bit to the wrong place,

43:36.364 --> 43:39.116
you might be dealing
with a whole other set of regulations.

43:39.284 --> 43:42.828
The tribe claimed that
because Maurice Williams,

43:43.329 --> 43:44.746
being a member of the tribe,

43:44.831 --> 43:49.459
had not purchased a $1 00 permit
to sell something,

43:49.711 --> 43:53.380
the fossil should be forfeited
and therefore they owned the fossil.

43:53.506 --> 43:56.425
And of course the government said
that it was government property

43:56.509 --> 44:00.554
and that, that was
because of the trust land issue.

44:07.478 --> 44:09.813
The seizure and the subpoena

44:09.897 --> 44:14.276
were the brainchild
of Acting U.S. Attorney Kevin Schieffer.

44:14.402 --> 44:17.612
HARLAN: He was a controversial
figure as a U.S. Attorney

44:17.739 --> 44:21.491
because he hadn't had
a lot of experience practicing law.

44:21.576 --> 44:24.369
He had the ability
to drive some people crazy.

44:24.495 --> 44:26.538
l do have a fair amount
of litigation experience.

44:26.622 --> 44:29.583
l have not had courtroom experience.

44:29.834 --> 44:31.168
PETER: It's a little unclear

44:31.252 --> 44:35.505
as to why Schieffer decided to seize Sue

44:35.590 --> 44:37.758
or decided to become
interested in this at all,

44:37.925 --> 44:42.012
whether it began with Maurice Williams
or a complaint from the tribe.

44:42.096 --> 44:44.765
Ultimately the decision
was Kevin Schieffer's, though,

44:44.891 --> 44:48.602
to decide that this was something
that they wanted to do.

44:53.775 --> 44:55.817
DUFFY: Also was shocking
from a scientific standpoint,

44:55.902 --> 44:57.819
that anybody would behave so recklessly

44:57.945 --> 45:00.822
with the greatest paleontological find
of all time.

45:00.990 --> 45:03.909
lf that dinosaur seizure
wasn't a publicity stunt,

45:03.993 --> 45:05.160
then l don't know what is.

45:05.244 --> 45:07.788
There could have been a gang in this town

45:07.914 --> 45:09.873
with a warehouse holding a ton of cocaine

45:09.957 --> 45:11.958
and human bodies hanging from the rafters,

45:12.043 --> 45:13.502
and the federal government
would not have sent

45:13.628 --> 45:15.670
35 agents and the National Guard.

45:17.507 --> 45:19.549
(MARCHlNG BAND PLAYlNG)

45:25.306 --> 45:27.391
Just a few of 'em, bumper stickers.

45:27.475 --> 45:28.725
There's some in every vehicle.

45:28.810 --> 45:30.936
We would just like to gain public support

45:31.020 --> 45:33.980
for our cause
of getting Sue back to Hill City.

45:34.148 --> 45:36.858
WENTZ: When you get the big foot
of the government come in

45:36.943 --> 45:39.069
and do something like that,
you better answer

45:39.153 --> 45:42.239
in a way that people can understand
that this is wrong.

45:42.448 --> 45:44.783
You know, they just protested
for three straight days

45:44.867 --> 45:47.869
in front of the lnstitute during the raid.

45:47.995 --> 45:50.580
They weren't done. "We want to protest."

45:50.665 --> 45:52.999
Okay. Let's go protest.

45:53.292 --> 45:55.293
(CHEERlNG)

46:05.471 --> 46:07.139
Stay back.

46:08.141 --> 46:09.599
Everyone, stay back.

46:09.684 --> 46:11.893
You'll be thrown to the ground and arrested.

46:11.978 --> 46:15.147
We got everything under control here.
We don't want any trouble.

46:15.440 --> 46:16.815
NEAL:
We had people from all over the community,

46:16.899 --> 46:18.692
all over the Black Hills
who were trying to help,

46:18.985 --> 46:20.944
and it was amazing, the support that we had.

46:21.028 --> 46:23.029
WENTZ: We were fighting on
every front that we could think of,

46:23.197 --> 46:24.448
everything that you could think of,

46:24.532 --> 46:29.119
everything from the Sue Freedom Run
to petitions that we took to the state capital.

46:29.203 --> 46:31.955
l would talk in front of groups anywhere.

46:32.039 --> 46:35.876
PETER: Terry was so involved in this case.
l mean, he lived it.

46:38.045 --> 46:40.589
One of the most moving things
in my life to see,

46:40.673 --> 46:42.716
this wonderful group of people here

46:42.884 --> 46:44.509
supported us getting Sue back.

46:53.561 --> 46:57.606
The U.S. Attorney, Mr. Kevin Schieffer,
made a terrible error

46:57.690 --> 47:00.859
in coming that tragic day
on May 1 4th to Hill City.

47:00.943 --> 47:05.197
The right thing to do in this case
would be to return the dinosaur to Hill City.

47:05.281 --> 47:07.282
(CHEERlNG AND APPLAUSE)

47:07.366 --> 47:09.326
MAN: Whoo! Yes, yes! Whoo!

47:09.410 --> 47:12.037
PETER: We got now over 20, 000 signatures

47:12.121 --> 47:15.081
on the one petition,
the first petition to bring Sue back,

47:15.416 --> 47:18.835
and they're from all 50 states
and from 1 4 other countries.

47:18.920 --> 47:20.879
MATKINS: A lot of people didn't have
a lot of money around here,

47:20.963 --> 47:22.881
so they wanted to contribute
any way they could do that,

47:22.965 --> 47:26.384
and so there were a lot of fundraisers,
parades, buttons, posters,

47:26.469 --> 47:28.929
a show of maybe there's justice,

47:29.555 --> 47:32.015
because, l think, to me,
it was just a huge injustice,

47:32.099 --> 47:33.433
the fact they could even do
what they've done.

47:33.559 --> 47:35.769
The custody battle was in full swing,

47:35.853 --> 47:39.231
and it was very dramatic
and scary for people.

47:39.690 --> 47:43.443
And as l interviewed Pete
and talked with him,

47:43.528 --> 47:46.696
I realized at that time
l'd never met anybody like him.

47:47.240 --> 47:51.201
ln his single-minded pursuit
of what he believed was right,

47:51.285 --> 47:54.371
and also, in the flurry of emotions,

47:54.622 --> 47:57.832
l thought that meant that
he was the perfect guy for me.

47:58.042 --> 48:00.877
And so despite the fact
that l was writing about him

48:00.962 --> 48:02.671
and he should be my subject,

48:02.964 --> 48:06.800
l broke the first rule of journalism
and fell in love with my subject.

48:07.677 --> 48:09.427
So we started dating,

48:09.512 --> 48:12.806
and in our emotional ridiculousness,

48:12.974 --> 48:17.143
got married really quite quickly,
within months of my moving here.

48:17.311 --> 48:19.479
But it was okay.

48:19.647 --> 48:21.565
lt was okay for what was going on there.

48:21.941 --> 48:24.526
And so we traversed this together,

48:24.610 --> 48:26.736
and l had created for myself

48:26.821 --> 48:28.738
the additional burden
of trying to be a journalist

48:28.823 --> 48:31.783
and separate my personal feelings
from my job.

48:44.505 --> 48:46.464
MALE REPORTER: Two federal courts
have sided with the government,

48:46.549 --> 48:48.091
saying Sue should stay in the box

48:48.175 --> 48:50.969
because there's no proof
the dinosaur is being damaged there.

48:51.220 --> 48:52.679
ln another federal court,

48:52.763 --> 48:56.224
they're still arguing over
who actually owns the bones.

48:56.350 --> 49:00.854
The intensity of reaction while the court
case was going on really surprised me.

49:00.938 --> 49:03.356
There were people that l thought
were quite reasonable people

49:03.983 --> 49:06.401
who basically

49:07.194 --> 49:09.571
said things about Black Hills
that just were not true.

49:09.655 --> 49:13.783
There's no question that S.V. P. ,
the Society of Vertebrate Paleontology,

49:13.868 --> 49:17.537
was aligned against Peter Larson
and the lnstitute

49:17.872 --> 49:19.497
from the beginning
and all the way to the end.

49:19.624 --> 49:22.792
PETER: I had been a member of the Society
for Vertebrate Paleontology since the '70s.

49:22.877 --> 49:27.756
The S.V.P. became very active in it, in that
they actually sent out two different letters.

49:27.840 --> 49:30.133
One was fully in support
of the U.S. Attorney's action

49:30.217 --> 49:33.219
in seizing the dinosaur, and the other one,
l think, was saying that,

49:33.346 --> 49:35.555
"Yes, it was kept in a perfectly good place."

49:35.723 --> 49:38.141
Which, you know, how can you say that
if you've never seen it?

49:38.225 --> 49:39.809
Many of them have very strong feelings

49:39.894 --> 49:43.271
about whether or not the specimen
should be commercially collected or not.

49:43.481 --> 49:44.648
There is a difference

49:44.732 --> 49:48.109
between the academic perspective

49:48.194 --> 49:49.653
of fossil collecting

49:49.737 --> 49:52.113
and the commercial perspective.

49:52.406 --> 49:56.493
There are some people in this profession
that really, truly believe that it is. . .

49:56.577 --> 49:59.079
There's something morally wrong
with selling a fossil.

49:59.163 --> 50:02.999
l was indoctrinated as an undergrad

50:03.084 --> 50:07.504
that if you don't have a PhD,
you have no right to collect dinosaurs.

50:07.588 --> 50:11.132
l heard about the BHl and Peter Larson
collecting fossils,

50:11.217 --> 50:13.635
and l was told, "These are pirates."

50:13.719 --> 50:18.098
And l visited Pete Larson,
and l visited the Black Hills lnstitute,

50:18.182 --> 50:20.100
and they weren't pirates at all.

50:20.267 --> 50:24.479
They had techniques they taught my crew.
They were better than my crew.

50:24.605 --> 50:27.065
You have academians,
and they have these little fiefdoms.

50:27.149 --> 50:30.235
They built these towers
and they all surround themselves

50:30.319 --> 50:32.612
because they're. . .
They're dependent on money

50:32.738 --> 50:36.366
from grants and other institutions
to do their work.

50:36.534 --> 50:39.911
And now here's these
really great paleontologists

50:39.995 --> 50:41.246
that don't need that system.

50:41.372 --> 50:44.290
She who sold seashells
on the seashore was Mary Anning.

50:44.709 --> 50:47.544
She sold fossils. She was a dealer.

50:47.628 --> 50:51.715
And she was one of the highest-ranked
ladies in science of the time.

50:51.799 --> 50:54.092
Back in the day, in the early 1 900s,

50:54.343 --> 50:58.680
"commercial collectors" were
filling museums with specimens

50:59.140 --> 51:02.475
and working hand-in-hand
with "academic people."

51:02.768 --> 51:04.436
That was an okay relationship.

51:04.520 --> 51:06.813
Around in the '70s and '80s, that changed.

51:06.981 --> 51:10.525
CURRlE:
1 980s, we're already seeing this schism

51:10.609 --> 51:13.069
between professional commercial collectors

51:13.154 --> 51:15.822
versus professional research collectors.

51:15.906 --> 51:19.826
This race to discover the Earth's past

51:20.369 --> 51:23.163
is a very exciting one,
and people want a piece of it.

51:27.668 --> 51:29.669
(DOG BARKS)

51:32.381 --> 51:34.758
DONNAN:
Through the pendency of the custody case,

51:34.842 --> 51:38.636
Pete's way of managing stress was to work.

51:38.763 --> 51:42.515
He also was extremely sad.

51:42.600 --> 51:46.060
lt was as if, often, he was in mourning.

51:46.187 --> 51:50.315
PETER: Sue had become a living entity
to me after all our work in the field

51:50.399 --> 51:52.150
and what we were finding out about her life.

51:52.234 --> 51:55.528
And l really missed her when she was gone.

51:56.322 --> 51:58.948
So one way that I was able to

51:59.408 --> 52:02.535
sort of help that was to go and visit her

52:03.120 --> 52:06.623
and to talk with her through the window,
looking at the container.

52:06.707 --> 52:09.542
So l could see her,
see that, that container's still there,

52:10.211 --> 52:13.421
not moved to some other place
in Timbuktu or something.

52:13.714 --> 52:18.510
And just kind of had
some little conversations with her.

52:21.347 --> 52:23.389
(MUSlC PLAYlNG)

52:37.696 --> 52:40.573
DONNAN: lt was precious. lt was...

52:41.367 --> 52:42.534
lt was sweet.

52:42.618 --> 52:45.578
She was his person,

52:45.788 --> 52:48.373
and later l would realize
she was more of his person

52:48.457 --> 52:53.670
than any other person
has ever been and ever will be.

52:53.921 --> 52:58.716
l got to say that dinosaur and Pete Larson
were made for each other.

52:59.051 --> 53:01.344
And so he had to go talk to her,

53:01.428 --> 53:03.388
and that was what. . . How it should be.

53:10.813 --> 53:15.024
PETER: Mostly l was trying to reassure her
that she wasn't going to rot in that case,

53:15.109 --> 53:16.818
that l was gonna spring her free,

53:16.944 --> 53:18.945
somehow l was going to get her out of there.

53:51.312 --> 53:54.355
As that whole custody battle unfolded,

53:54.440 --> 53:57.734
firstly the tribe lost
its own case in tribal court,

53:57.818 --> 54:02.739
which is pretty surprising,
but evident that it was a bad claim.

54:02.823 --> 54:04.991
The government actually retracted its claim

54:05.075 --> 54:07.827
because it realized
it couldn't claim trust property.

54:08.037 --> 54:09.829
So then it comes down to two people.

54:09.955 --> 54:12.707
ls it Maurice's fossil,
or is it Black Hills lnstitute's fossil?

54:12.875 --> 54:15.835
Every single filing the lnstitute made,

54:16.378 --> 54:20.256
l really believed would win
because it was so clear.

54:20.424 --> 54:24.093
They had purchased it.
He had accepted the check.

54:24.720 --> 54:27.347
He had been on videotape talking about it.

54:27.514 --> 54:32.060
lt was very clear that he thought
he had sold the fossil at the time.

54:40.778 --> 54:43.488
DUFFY: Judge Battey held

54:43.656 --> 54:45.490
that a fossil,

54:45.574 --> 54:48.534
unlike an archeological find,

54:48.744 --> 54:52.413
had become. . .
The bones had become mineralized.

54:52.581 --> 54:57.001
Therefore, the fossil was land.

54:57.419 --> 55:02.465
An individual lndian cannot sell land

55:02.549 --> 55:04.842
that the government holds in trust for him

55:05.094 --> 55:06.844
without the permission

55:07.304 --> 55:09.347
of the federal government to begin with.

55:09.723 --> 55:11.391
So that's what ended it.

55:11.600 --> 55:12.976
Fossils are land.

55:23.070 --> 55:25.989
Judge Battey said actually in his filing

55:26.073 --> 55:28.074
that the sale was null and void.

55:28.158 --> 55:31.869
The federal government took the position
that he had no authority himself

55:31.954 --> 55:34.414
to enter into an agreement
with the Black Hills lnstitute.

55:34.540 --> 55:38.876
Peter realized that
he could not have his fossil back.

55:39.253 --> 55:40.378
He was devastated.

55:40.546 --> 55:43.589
The judge decided that Sue was real estate.

55:45.551 --> 55:47.010
Sue, the fossil, was real estate.

55:48.929 --> 55:51.014
For Peter, it was uniquely heartbreaking.

55:51.932 --> 55:53.433
Maybe we're done.

55:54.059 --> 55:56.769
Maybe taking

55:56.895 --> 56:00.481
from Peter Larson the sum of all
his boyhood dreams

56:00.858 --> 56:02.567
would be enough punishment

56:02.693 --> 56:06.112
to end everything that Schieffer had began.

56:22.629 --> 56:25.923
l first got involved in the dinosaur case,
as we called it,

56:26.300 --> 56:31.179
sometime late 1 992, early 1 993.

56:31.680 --> 56:33.222
Of course they're not gonna
like what we're doing.

56:33.307 --> 56:35.516
That's the nature of what we do.

56:35.601 --> 56:39.520
But, hopefully, in a broader spectrum,
people can look at it and say,

56:39.646 --> 56:43.816
"Well, l'm glad people can't just go out
into the forest or go out onto the parks

56:43.901 --> 56:46.819
"and take these fossils or. . ."

56:46.904 --> 56:50.490
ln this particular case,
"Or steal stuff off some land,

56:50.574 --> 56:51.783
"and somebody's going
to do something about it."

56:51.867 --> 56:53.493
Well, we're the somebody
that does something about it.

57:01.668 --> 57:04.378
SANTUCCl:
After the seizure of the Sue specimen,

57:04.505 --> 57:07.507
we continued to look at this issue

57:07.591 --> 57:10.760
not from a Park Service
jurisdiction perspective,

57:10.844 --> 57:14.889
but more from the circumstances
of business practices

57:15.015 --> 57:17.058
in terms of collecting on public lands.

57:25.859 --> 57:29.862
You really can't do anything
in any kind of a business without money.

57:30.239 --> 57:32.824
What monetary transactions happened

57:32.908 --> 57:36.202
during the time that this enterprise
had that fossil,

57:36.328 --> 57:38.204
and then what did they do with that fossil?

57:38.413 --> 57:40.581
Sell it? What happened to that money?

57:40.749 --> 57:44.335
And then how we could assemble
the evidence around that fossil

57:44.461 --> 57:47.171
to see whether there's
something there that's wrong,

57:47.422 --> 57:50.133
chargeable,
what more needs to be investigated.

57:50.217 --> 57:51.968
MALE REPORTER:
FBI agents arrived here in Hill City.

57:52.052 --> 57:54.595
They presented the Black Hills lnstitute
with a court order.

57:54.721 --> 57:57.390
That order demanded
the release of more information.

57:57.474 --> 57:59.851
But the people at the lnstitute
have another name for it.

57:59.935 --> 58:01.102
They call it harassment.

58:01.395 --> 58:02.520
WOMAN:
This should not be allowed to happen.

58:02.604 --> 58:04.397
This is the United States of America.

58:08.235 --> 58:11.195
MALE REPORTER 2: So far, no criminal
charges have been filed in the case.

58:11.280 --> 58:13.823
Members of the Institute
say they're innocent

58:13.907 --> 58:15.825
and are hoping that a new administration

58:15.909 --> 58:18.536
will put an end to their legal fight over Sue.

58:25.377 --> 58:27.587
MALE REPORTER 3: lnstitute officials
thought their problems were over

58:27.671 --> 58:29.755
when Kevin Schieffer
was replaced as U.S. Attorney,

58:29.840 --> 58:32.508
but apparently they continue to be
the target of the federal government.

58:32.593 --> 58:36.179
We have a federal search warrant
issued by the U.S. District Court,

58:36.263 --> 58:37.597
and we're serving a search warrant.

58:37.681 --> 58:39.849
DRUE VlTTER: Enormous amount
of money that the government's spending

58:39.933 --> 58:41.267
to put one person out...

58:41.435 --> 58:44.687
One group of people out of business
that's so vital to a community.

58:44.771 --> 58:48.149
lt's been nearly 1 8 months
since Sue was seized from this warehouse,

58:48.233 --> 58:50.568
and still no charges have been filed
against the lnstitute.

58:50.652 --> 58:53.070
Allow us some rights.
Charge us with something,

58:53.155 --> 58:55.281
and let's go to court. Let 1 2 people decide.

59:05.459 --> 59:07.710
HENDRlCKSON:
l couldn't give them any information

59:07.794 --> 59:10.838
to help incriminate people
at Black Hills lnstitute.

59:10.923 --> 59:12.506
They thought l was
going to be able tell them

59:12.591 --> 59:16.010
all sorts of terrible things the lnstitute did.

59:16.178 --> 59:17.595
Well, they didn't do anything wrong.

59:17.679 --> 59:18.971
They talked to my attorney about,

59:19.056 --> 59:22.308
"You better get your guy in
and bring him on in,

59:22.476 --> 59:24.977
"or, you know, last chance
happening pretty soon."

59:25.062 --> 59:28.272
And my attorney says,
"He just doesn't have anything to tell you."

59:28.607 --> 59:31.943
HENDRlCKSON: For three years,
I had no contact with the Institute.

59:32.152 --> 59:34.779
That's horrible. l mean,
l considered them best friends,

59:34.905 --> 59:36.447
and l couldn't call them up.

59:37.282 --> 59:40.743
FARRAR: Sue was probably the impetus

59:40.827 --> 59:45.081
for the government following up
with a criminal prosecution.

59:45.165 --> 59:49.126
Sue wasn't a part of what we were looking at
or what was being looked at

59:49.211 --> 59:51.420
as far as potential criminal violations.

59:51.505 --> 59:53.089
There were so many bones,

59:53.173 --> 59:56.092
so many animals, so many invertebrates

59:56.301 --> 59:58.678
that were taken off from public lands,

59:58.762 --> 01:00:01.389
taken internationally, sold internationally.

01:00:01.515 --> 01:00:03.432
There was way more than
we could have ever investigated.

01:00:03.517 --> 01:00:05.935
The case was never wanting
for not having Sue.

01:00:07.771 --> 01:00:11.440
HARLAN:
Because so much material had been seized,

01:00:11.525 --> 01:00:16.070
l think everybody thought
that there would be a massive indictment.

01:00:16.613 --> 01:00:17.905
MAN:
Tell me a little bit about today's indictment.

01:00:17.990 --> 01:00:21.409
What alleged activity
are we exactly talking about?

01:00:21.493 --> 01:00:24.870
ROBERT MANDEL:
This indictment charges the theft of fossils

01:00:24.955 --> 01:00:27.915
off a number of different types
of federal land.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:32.628
There are also charges in there
that pertain to money laundering,

01:00:32.713 --> 01:00:34.714
structuring of currency transactions,

01:00:34.798 --> 01:00:38.467
false statements made
to various government agencies.

01:00:38.552 --> 01:00:41.012
HARLAN: The indictments
were an avalanche of charges,

01:00:41.096 --> 01:00:43.097
and it was just a massive document,

01:00:43.223 --> 01:00:46.726
and it looked like
a deathblow to the lnstitute.

01:00:46.935 --> 01:00:49.353
The government went just nuts
or something, you know?

01:00:49.438 --> 01:00:50.438
l mean, they tried. . .

01:00:50.522 --> 01:00:53.107
l guess they just threw everything in
and hoped something would stick.

01:00:53.358 --> 01:00:55.651
PETER: lf you add up the time to serve
for each of those counts,

01:00:55.736 --> 01:00:58.029
it comes to 353 years for me,

01:00:58.155 --> 01:01:03.701
which is longer than Jeffrey Dahmer
was sentenced to prison for,

01:01:03.785 --> 01:01:05.995
and he killed and ate, like, 1 3 people.

01:01:06.079 --> 01:01:07.747
You know, it doesn't make sense.

01:01:07.831 --> 01:01:14.170
A lot of these accusations are
things that we know were legal.

01:01:14.254 --> 01:01:17.965
Thirty-eight felony indictments
for collecting fossils?

01:01:18.258 --> 01:01:21.344
HENDRlCKSON: lt totally blew me apart.

01:01:21.511 --> 01:01:24.680
l'm used to fixing things,
and this was unfixable,

01:01:24.765 --> 01:01:26.015
and it was so stupid.

01:01:26.099 --> 01:01:28.059
Once you start to
understand the indictments,

01:01:28.143 --> 01:01:30.227
basically this is what they said.

01:01:30.312 --> 01:01:32.021
Pretend we're in Wyoming

01:01:32.105 --> 01:01:34.023
and we're standing
in the middle of the prairie,

01:01:34.107 --> 01:01:35.608
and let's assume for a moment

01:01:35.692 --> 01:01:37.985
that the fence is in the right place.

01:01:38.945 --> 01:01:41.906
You're standing on this side of the fence.
The government says right over there,

01:01:41.990 --> 01:01:44.867
on the other side of the fence,
is this fabulous fossil,

01:01:44.951 --> 01:01:46.285
and they're basically saying

01:01:46.370 --> 01:01:50.206
that Pete and Neal and Bob
and whoever was out there would go,

01:01:50.290 --> 01:01:51.791
step over the fence,

01:01:52.167 --> 01:01:55.961
wrongly, knowingly pick up the fossil
that they're not supposed to pick up,

01:01:56.713 --> 01:01:59.382
carry it back over the fence,
put it in their car.

01:01:59.549 --> 01:02:02.134
When they drive from Wyoming
to South Dakota,

01:02:02.302 --> 01:02:05.471
they then have conducted
an illegal act, which is called

01:02:05.597 --> 01:02:08.891
the interstate transportation
of stolen property.

01:02:08.975 --> 01:02:10.684
They get back to the lnstitute.

01:02:10.811 --> 01:02:14.563
They would make a phone call,
send a fax, maybe to Japan, and say,

01:02:14.648 --> 01:02:17.024
"We found the thing
that you were looking for.

01:02:17.484 --> 01:02:18.901
"Do you want to buy it?"

01:02:18.985 --> 01:02:20.694
Well, that's wire fraud.

01:02:20.779 --> 01:02:26.075
And then if the Japanese museum
were to purchase that fossil

01:02:26.159 --> 01:02:29.370
and the guys would put that money
in the bank, that's money laundering.

01:02:29.454 --> 01:02:32.957
So basically the guys
were called conspirators

01:02:33.041 --> 01:02:37.628
who were creating
this very elaborate scheme

01:02:37.712 --> 01:02:40.965
to intentionally steal things
and sell them illegally.

01:02:41.133 --> 01:02:44.301
Mafioso master criminals,
Pete, Neal, and Bob.

01:02:44.386 --> 01:02:45.636
(LAUGHS)

01:02:47.055 --> 01:02:49.098
Yeah, they tried to paint a picture that was. . .

01:02:49.182 --> 01:02:51.350
l mean, you know, they're. . .

01:02:51.435 --> 01:02:52.768
Pete and Neal are a couple of kids

01:02:52.853 --> 01:02:56.313
that learned how to love fossil collecting
as kids on the ranch.

01:02:56.398 --> 01:02:58.190
To think that all of a sudden they decided

01:02:58.275 --> 01:03:01.444
to become thieves or something
is just insane.

01:03:18.503 --> 01:03:19.795
NEAL: As the months went by,

01:03:19.880 --> 01:03:23.007
things seemed to get darker
and darker and darker.

01:03:23.383 --> 01:03:26.719
For quite a while, we'd hoped
that they'll gain their senses

01:03:26.803 --> 01:03:28.137
and this'll just go away.

01:03:28.221 --> 01:03:31.557
Because it was
so hotly contested along the way,

01:03:32.058 --> 01:03:36.479
l didn't think there would be any chance
that this case would settle before trial.

01:03:36.563 --> 01:03:40.858
By late summer of '94,
there were serious discussions

01:03:40.942 --> 01:03:43.235
that were going on with
the U.S. Attorney's office

01:03:43.361 --> 01:03:44.653
for a possible resolution.

01:03:44.738 --> 01:03:46.655
l go out on my step one morning

01:03:46.740 --> 01:03:48.157
and bring the Rapid City Journal in

01:03:48.241 --> 01:03:50.493
and have a cup of coffee,
and right on the front page

01:03:50.744 --> 01:03:52.203
is the plea agreement announced.

01:03:54.915 --> 01:03:59.126
NEAL: Somebody spilled their guts
in front of Hugh O'Gara,

01:03:59.252 --> 01:04:01.587
and he might as well have taken a gun
and shot us.

01:04:01.755 --> 01:04:05.633
DUFFY:
The article itself suggested capitulation

01:04:05.717 --> 01:04:06.926
on the part of the government.

01:04:07.010 --> 01:04:08.594
You never get a good deal done

01:04:08.762 --> 01:04:13.015
if somebody is going to be cast
as having folded their tent.

01:04:13.099 --> 01:04:15.518
DONNAN: Anybody who would
publish that should know better.

01:04:15.602 --> 01:04:19.438
So I called Hugh O'Gara,
and l just said, "What were you thinking?

01:04:20.065 --> 01:04:21.357
"How could you do that?"

01:04:21.441 --> 01:04:23.234
And he was near tears on the phone.

01:04:23.318 --> 01:04:24.652
He would not answer me.

01:04:24.861 --> 01:04:28.572
Hugh would never. . . Obviously,
would not tell me who that source was.

01:04:28.657 --> 01:04:29.823
l wouldn't even ask him.

01:04:29.950 --> 01:04:31.158
PETER: The next morning,

01:04:31.243 --> 01:04:34.245
the judge called
all the attorneys into chambers.

01:04:34.454 --> 01:04:37.206
DUFFY: He went down the line
and made each of us say

01:04:37.290 --> 01:04:39.917
that we were not responsible for the leak.

01:04:40.126 --> 01:04:43.796
He felt that the principals at least
deserved to go to jail.

01:04:43.964 --> 01:04:45.923
He said that he would not accept the plea.

01:04:46.049 --> 01:04:49.969
He had prejudged the case,
and under two federal statutes

01:04:50.178 --> 01:04:52.888
a judge is obligated to remove themselves

01:04:52.973 --> 01:04:54.932
from sitting and hearing the rest of the case.

01:04:55.100 --> 01:04:56.475
So we filed immediately

01:04:56.560 --> 01:05:00.563
our second recusal motion,
asking the judge to step down.

01:05:00.647 --> 01:05:03.107
The thing that seems to
upset Judge Battey the most

01:05:03.191 --> 01:05:05.401
is not whether he's fair,

01:05:05.485 --> 01:05:07.528
but to be challenged that he's not being fair.

01:05:07.737 --> 01:05:09.363
So he immediately denied that motion.

01:05:22.669 --> 01:05:25.337
l knew this case was going to trial

01:05:25.755 --> 01:05:30.467
the day the Hugh O'Gara article
was published in the Rapid City Journal.

01:05:52.532 --> 01:05:57.036
PETER: l'm not afraid of 1 2 people,
a jury of 1 2 people of our peers.

01:05:57.370 --> 01:06:01.123
l know that they'll look at this case
and they'll see the ridiculous way

01:06:01.207 --> 01:06:04.710
in which the government is behaving,
and they will vindicate us.

01:06:05.253 --> 01:06:07.546
We're innocent of all the things
that we're charged with.

01:06:22.479 --> 01:06:23.520
PETER: So in the courtroom,

01:06:23.605 --> 01:06:27.775
of course, right in front
is Judge Battey in the bench.

01:06:27.859 --> 01:06:31.654
Off to the left is the jury,
1 2 jurors, two alternates,

01:06:31.738 --> 01:06:34.323
a large space in between where the lawyers

01:06:34.407 --> 01:06:36.492
get to pace and walk
and show exhibits and things,

01:06:36.576 --> 01:06:41.288
and then we have the prosecution,
which had at times two or three lawyers.

01:06:43.166 --> 01:06:45.334
On our side, there was
a lawyer for each defendant,

01:06:45.418 --> 01:06:48.420
so there are six lawyers and five defendants.

01:06:48.713 --> 01:06:52.424
The sixth defendant, of course,
being the Black Hills lnstitute.

01:06:52.759 --> 01:06:55.511
Our trial was, and still is,
the largest criminal case

01:06:55.595 --> 01:06:56.929
that's ever been tried in South Dakota.

01:07:00.100 --> 01:07:03.102
WENTZ:
You cannot say the word "Sue" in the trial.

01:07:04.062 --> 01:07:07.022
l mean, the jurors were going,
"What happened to Sue?

01:07:07.107 --> 01:07:10.109
"That's why they got these guys
in the court system, right?"

01:07:10.193 --> 01:07:12.945
The logistics of this trial
were incomprehensible.

01:07:19.619 --> 01:07:22.287
The lnstitute has collected
maybe a million fossils.

01:07:22.622 --> 01:07:25.374
This indictment covers 1 4 of them,

01:07:26.251 --> 01:07:29.586
and those 1 4 fossils
were collected from seven sites.

01:07:29.796 --> 01:07:31.672
ln seven cases,

01:07:31.756 --> 01:07:34.049
in all the years these guys
have been out in the field,

01:07:34.134 --> 01:07:36.468
they are accused of
being in the wrong place.

01:07:36.594 --> 01:07:38.721
ELLlSON: The government would
simply have their officials come in

01:07:38.805 --> 01:07:44.226
of whatever agency was going to be
taking the lead for that particular site

01:07:44.644 --> 01:07:47.062
and would say,
"l found where the specimen was collected.

01:07:47.147 --> 01:07:49.148
"l knew, therefore,
it was on government land."

01:07:49.274 --> 01:07:53.235
To me, it just emphasized
the ridiculous nature of this whole thing.

01:07:53.403 --> 01:07:55.237
You know, l mean, if it's 200 feet over

01:07:55.321 --> 01:07:57.656
and you don't know where you are,
it would have been okay?

01:08:02.287 --> 01:08:05.914
DONNAN: His job had been to appraise
the fossils that had been seized in the case,

01:08:06.374 --> 01:08:09.793
and his evaluations
would be incredibly important

01:08:09.878 --> 01:08:14.506
because they determined whether a given
count was a misdemeanor or a felony.

01:08:16.843 --> 01:08:19.720
lt was pretty easy in cross-examination

01:08:19.804 --> 01:08:24.308
to discover that the man
had not opened the field jackets.

01:08:24.684 --> 01:08:29.188
He was telling us the values of things
he had not even looked at.

01:08:51.461 --> 01:08:56.298
HENDRlCKSON: Pete and l, on one of our
trips to Peru, we were taking $1 5,000 in cash

01:08:56.381 --> 01:09:00.385
because down there
you can't use credit cards or anything else.

01:09:01.345 --> 01:09:04.223
And he withdrew $1 5,000 from the bank,
and we split it up.

01:09:04.307 --> 01:09:07.643
Just in case one person got robbed,
at least they wouldn't lose everything.

01:09:07.727 --> 01:09:09.812
Susan Hendrickson carried 8,000

01:09:09.895 --> 01:09:12.856
and l carried $7,000 down
one of the trips, of cash.

01:09:12.941 --> 01:09:16.568
We were building a museum,
paying for the bricks and mortar

01:09:16.653 --> 01:09:18.862
and doing the work ourselves
with our Swiss colleagues.

01:09:27.538 --> 01:09:30.457
HENDRlCKSON: ln Japan, they..
The museums pay in cash.

01:09:30.542 --> 01:09:34.169
They always have. Didn't want to
carry bundles of cash on the plane,

01:09:34.254 --> 01:09:36.505
so we went to a bank
and put it in traveler's checks.

01:09:36.589 --> 01:09:38.799
They were all restrictively
endorsed traveler's checks,

01:09:38.883 --> 01:09:42.636
all stamped for deposit only,
deposited in the bank. Paid taxes on them.

01:09:42.929 --> 01:09:45.013
Prosecution had four different witnesses,

01:09:45.098 --> 01:09:48.015
all of whom testified that
restrictively endorsed traveler's checks

01:09:48.100 --> 01:09:49.350
do not need to be declared.

01:09:49.435 --> 01:09:52.354
What struck me about
the prosecution's case

01:09:52.438 --> 01:09:54.022
was how complex it was.

01:09:54.107 --> 01:09:58.902
People had to understand
the arcane ins and outs

01:09:59.070 --> 01:10:02.990
of bringing traveler's checks
into the country

01:10:03.116 --> 01:10:06.451
and latitudes and longitudes
on public lands.

01:10:06.703 --> 01:10:09.246
And l think they did it in an organized way,

01:10:09.414 --> 01:10:12.291
but it was a very,
very complicated argument.

01:10:17.338 --> 01:10:19.214
KElTH NELSON: When the prosecution rested,

01:10:19.465 --> 01:10:23.051
l felt we had put on
the evidence that we had.

01:10:23.136 --> 01:10:26.179
We had their own pictures
of them taking these fossils.

01:10:26.264 --> 01:10:29.349
We had their own field notes
of them collecting these fossils.

01:10:29.642 --> 01:10:34.813
We had given it 1 00% of our effort
to show what they did.

01:10:37.609 --> 01:10:39.985
DONNAN:
As the defense proceeded to present

01:10:40.069 --> 01:10:42.112
many fewer witnesses to say,

01:10:42.780 --> 01:10:44.156
"Look, it's not that complicated.

01:10:44.240 --> 01:10:47.451
"We were collecting fossils.
We thought we had permission to be there.

01:10:47.577 --> 01:10:49.536
"ln this case, we weren't
where you thought we were.

01:10:49.621 --> 01:10:51.914
"ln this case, we were. lt's that simple."

01:10:56.669 --> 01:10:59.838
ELLlSON: As we were approaching
the end of the trial, Neal and l both felt

01:10:59.923 --> 01:11:02.633
that it was important for him to testify.

01:11:02.717 --> 01:11:04.301
NEAL: Three-and-a-half days,
l was on the witness stand,

01:11:04.385 --> 01:11:06.261
and for three-and-a-half days,

01:11:06.346 --> 01:11:11.099
l swore to tell the truth, the whole truth,
and nothing but the truth, so help me God.

01:11:18.358 --> 01:11:20.233
DONNAN: Pete ended up not testifying.

01:11:20.485 --> 01:11:22.027
State had not proven its case.

01:11:22.320 --> 01:11:26.198
The state doesn't prove their case,
your client doesn't take the stand, period.

01:11:27.241 --> 01:11:30.702
And so on the advice of counsel,
l did not testify.

01:11:49.889 --> 01:11:51.348
FEMALE REPORTER:
The jury came back today

01:11:51.432 --> 01:11:53.642
in the Hill City fossil hunter
federal criminal trial.

01:11:53.726 --> 01:11:56.019
The jury said over and over again

01:11:56.104 --> 01:12:00.399
either not guilty
or no unanimous verdict could be reached.

01:12:00.483 --> 01:12:02.484
Of over 1 50 charges,

01:12:02.568 --> 01:12:05.237
the jury agreed to convict only 1 3 times,

01:12:05.405 --> 01:12:07.823
and five of those convictions
are for misdemeanor crimes.

01:12:08.032 --> 01:12:10.659
So here is how the convictions break down.

01:12:10.743 --> 01:12:13.078
Pete Larson, co-owner
and founder of the lnstitute,

01:12:13.162 --> 01:12:15.622
is convicted on two counts
of misdemeanor thefts

01:12:15.707 --> 01:12:18.250
and two felony counts
of illegally transporting money

01:12:18.334 --> 01:12:19.668
in and out of the country.

01:12:19.752 --> 01:12:23.255
Brother Neal Larson found guilty
of one misdemeanor theft.

01:12:23.423 --> 01:12:27.384
The jury either acquitted Neal
or couldn't agree on a verdict for the others.

01:12:27.468 --> 01:12:30.429
Bob Farrar, a third co-owner of the lnstitute,

01:12:30.555 --> 01:12:32.097
convicted of two felonies,

01:12:32.181 --> 01:12:34.975
making false statements
to customs officials.

01:12:35.059 --> 01:12:37.269
And the Black Hills Institute
as a corporation

01:12:37.353 --> 01:12:40.313
is convicted of two misdemeanor thefts,
a felony theft,

01:12:40.440 --> 01:12:43.275
and twice making false statements
to customs officials.

01:12:43.359 --> 01:12:45.193
The jury also found the lnstitute

01:12:45.278 --> 01:12:48.697
guilty of bringing goods into the States
by making a false statement.

01:12:48.948 --> 01:12:53.493
Defendants Eddie Cole and Terry Wentz
were not convicted on any charges.

01:12:58.624 --> 01:13:03.045
As the verdict was announced,
it was almost impossible to believe

01:13:03.129 --> 01:13:05.881
that the defense
hadn't scored a great victory.

01:13:05.965 --> 01:13:11.470
However, there were some
fairly significant felony convictions.

01:13:11.554 --> 01:13:13.972
The expression, "You could have
knocked me over with a feather. . ."

01:13:15.475 --> 01:13:16.892
You could have
knocked me over with a feather.

01:13:16.976 --> 01:13:19.061
Four times guilty,

01:13:19.145 --> 01:13:20.896
and l'm trying to look and see,
what is Pat saying?

01:13:20.980 --> 01:13:22.147
"Don't look at it." Then he says,

01:13:22.231 --> 01:13:24.941
"You follow me out of this courtroom,
and l don't want you to say one word."

01:13:25.026 --> 01:13:28.236
We got on the elevator, just me and Pete.

01:13:28.321 --> 01:13:32.532
Hit one. Started to go down.
Pete said, "l'm finished."

01:13:32.700 --> 01:13:35.202
He said, "These convictions
will completely destroy the lnstitute."

01:13:35.995 --> 01:13:41.458
l opened up my suit and l said,
"l got the best prop in the entire world."

01:13:41.834 --> 01:13:45.837
NELSON: Duffy, as soon as he hit the door,
had a big ol' cigar in his mouth,

01:13:46.130 --> 01:13:49.132
and as he's kind of
holding fort with the media,

01:13:49.217 --> 01:13:51.093
he's puffing away on his cigar, saying

01:13:51.177 --> 01:13:54.930
that he had won the case,
when he pretty much had to know,

01:13:55.014 --> 01:13:57.057
at that moment in time,
that at least his defendant

01:13:57.141 --> 01:13:59.184
was gonna be going to jail for a time

01:13:59.560 --> 01:14:01.561
and was gonna come away from it
a convicted felon.

01:14:01.687 --> 01:14:03.897
What l think the cigar did

01:14:03.981 --> 01:14:06.983
was just provide a graphic representation,

01:14:07.068 --> 01:14:10.487
easy for anyone to understand,
that all was not lost,

01:14:10.613 --> 01:14:13.115
that the word "guilty"
did not mean the end of the world,

01:14:13.324 --> 01:14:18.245
and that the town's, you know,
favorite paleontologists were okay.

01:14:42.770 --> 01:14:44.813
HARLAN:
l talked to some jurors after the trail.

01:14:44.897 --> 01:14:47.315
Some of them were near tears

01:14:47.400 --> 01:14:50.235
when l interviewed them,
about how they had hoped

01:14:50.319 --> 01:14:52.612
they could acquit on every single charge.

01:14:52.697 --> 01:14:55.490
LaNlCE ARCHER: l believed they had to have
something to take this to trial,

01:14:55.575 --> 01:14:58.034
and l spend the whole trial
waiting for that something.

01:14:58.327 --> 01:15:00.120
Without a doubt,

01:15:00.204 --> 01:15:03.331
the majority of the jurors

01:15:03.416 --> 01:15:06.001
wanted this whole case
dropped and put away.

01:15:15.219 --> 01:15:17.179
FEMALE REPORTER: Maurice Williams,
the rancher who found Sue,

01:15:17.263 --> 01:15:20.390
has received at least six offers
to purchase the T. rex.

01:15:20.516 --> 01:15:24.394
Since the courts determined that the fossil
is part of Williams' trust property,

01:15:24.478 --> 01:15:27.189
any purchase must be approved
by the federal government.

01:15:27.273 --> 01:15:30.317
Since Sue was seized
by federal agents in 1 992,

01:15:30.443 --> 01:15:32.777
the fossil has been stored
at the School of Mines.

01:15:32.945 --> 01:15:35.071
MURDY:
My first contact with Mr. Maurice Williams

01:15:35.239 --> 01:15:38.783
was when he came to Aberdeen
for a series of meetings

01:15:39.243 --> 01:15:45.332
to discuss what he should do
with this fossil.

01:15:45.416 --> 01:15:48.376
The idea that l had was to convene,

01:15:48.461 --> 01:15:51.213
like, a panel of paleontologists

01:15:51.464 --> 01:15:54.341
to do an in-depth study of this fossil

01:15:54.425 --> 01:15:56.885
with the hope that it would end up
in a museum somewhere.

01:15:56.969 --> 01:16:00.055
But in the meantime,
while this was being discussed,

01:16:00.973 --> 01:16:04.392
Mr. Williams decided that
he would rather sell the fossil.

01:16:09.523 --> 01:16:11.816
DAVlD REDDEN:
Maurice Williams had a stack of proposals

01:16:11.901 --> 01:16:13.944
from all sorts of people all over the place.

01:16:14.028 --> 01:16:15.111
l mean, everybody wanted it.

01:16:15.196 --> 01:16:16.655
l called up Maurice and l said,

01:16:16.739 --> 01:16:18.740
"l'm going to come out to South Dakota
if you want,

01:16:18.824 --> 01:16:22.577
"and l'll visit with you,"
and he said, "Great."

01:16:22.662 --> 01:16:27.666
And l actually visited the boxes
in which Sue was located

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:30.085
in the South Dakota School of Mines

01:16:30.169 --> 01:16:33.922
with Maurice's family,
who had never actually been there.

01:16:34.006 --> 01:16:36.341
This was the first time
they'd actually seen Sue.

01:16:36.509 --> 01:16:39.928
What one really saw
inside that sort of garage area

01:16:40.012 --> 01:16:41.680
was this extraordinary,

01:16:41.806 --> 01:16:45.684
almost Citizen Kane vision
of boxes and boxes and boxes.

01:16:46.852 --> 01:16:48.979
Maurice and I had numerous conversations.

01:16:49.063 --> 01:16:51.439
We talked about the responsibility involved

01:16:51.524 --> 01:16:54.651
in dealing with this extraordinary fossil.

01:16:54.735 --> 01:16:56.987
Nothing quite like it
had ever been sold before.

01:16:57.071 --> 01:16:58.863
lt had to go to the right place,

01:16:58.948 --> 01:17:03.034
but adjudicating which place
was the right place was complicated,

01:17:03.119 --> 01:17:06.037
and the auction process, in fact,
could help resolve that.

01:17:20.428 --> 01:17:24.264
PETER: We're going into court.
We'd already had an indication

01:17:24.348 --> 01:17:28.935
that the judge wasn't too pleased with us
because we asked him to recuse himself.

01:17:29.020 --> 01:17:35.191
lt was pretty clear that Judge Battey
was irritated by the defense.

01:17:35.401 --> 01:17:37.319
NEAL: We had to go back to the same tables

01:17:37.403 --> 01:17:40.864
with our attorneys and sit there,
and then stand up

01:17:40.948 --> 01:17:43.325
as Judge Battey sentenced us.

01:17:43.409 --> 01:17:47.037
He also wanted to hear
that we were sorry for what we had done.

01:17:54.003 --> 01:17:55.420
DUFFY: For Peter Larson,

01:17:55.504 --> 01:17:58.089
recommended guideline range

01:17:58.424 --> 01:18:01.134
for the two felonies
of which he was convicted

01:18:01.218 --> 01:18:02.844
was zero to six months.

01:18:02.928 --> 01:18:07.557
lt really looked like the sentence
would be minimal, probably probation.

01:18:07.767 --> 01:18:09.309
When he did come down with his sentence,

01:18:09.393 --> 01:18:12.312
he enhanced it,
so instead of zero to six months,

01:18:13.022 --> 01:18:15.940
he sentenced me to two years in prison
and two years probation.

01:18:27.536 --> 01:18:32.540
To send him to jail, to prison for two years
for this offense

01:18:32.666 --> 01:18:36.294
was absolutely no justification for it.

01:18:36.379 --> 01:18:40.757
lndefensible, ugly behavior.

01:18:40.841 --> 01:18:44.177
This is justice? This is,
you know, the country we live in?

01:18:44.261 --> 01:18:48.139
Every geographic photographer
in the last 30 years would be in jail.

01:18:48.224 --> 01:18:49.891
You know, you're coming back with $1 0,000.

01:18:49.975 --> 01:18:51.893
Well, you reported it going in.
You come back out.

01:18:51.977 --> 01:18:53.561
Do you report it?
No, because they're not countersigned.

01:18:53.646 --> 01:18:55.230
The reason the judge did is because

01:18:55.314 --> 01:18:58.733
he had been urged,
he had been convinced by guys with PhDs

01:18:58.818 --> 01:19:02.028
at university museums
that it had to be done,

01:19:02.154 --> 01:19:06.616
for the safety of our science and
our fossils, and that was so totally wrong.

01:19:06.700 --> 01:19:08.993
Peter Larson was made an example. . .

01:19:10.663 --> 01:19:11.955
. . .with that sentence.

01:19:12.915 --> 01:19:17.710
l don't have a real good recollection
of those. . .

01:19:20.172 --> 01:19:22.507
Those next few hours,
l guess you might say.

01:19:22.591 --> 01:19:25.593
FEMALE REPORTER: A federaljudge in
Rapid City today sentenced Peter Larson

01:19:25.678 --> 01:19:28.972
to two years in prison and a $5,000 fine.

01:19:29.056 --> 01:19:31.182
Larson was found guilty last year of charges

01:19:31.267 --> 01:19:34.185
connected to his commercial
fossil-hunting business in Hill City.

01:19:34.270 --> 01:19:36.438
lt's the final chapter in the case that began

01:19:36.522 --> 01:19:39.732
with the discovery of Sue,
the most complete Tyrannosaurus rex.

01:20:35.956 --> 01:20:39.501
PETER: l was to turn myself in at the gate,

01:20:39.585 --> 01:20:43.171
the same prison that
Timothy McVeigh was and John Gotti.

01:20:43.255 --> 01:20:45.965
And l was using a cane. l could barely walk.

01:20:46.050 --> 01:20:49.219
Just a few months before that,
broken my leg quite badly.

01:20:49.303 --> 01:20:52.388
When l surrendered at the gate,
they said, "We're gonna take your cane."

01:20:52.473 --> 01:20:55.517
l said, "lf you take my cane,
l'm going to fall over."

01:20:55.601 --> 01:20:57.894
Because l really couldn't
stand without my cane.

01:20:57.978 --> 01:20:59.437
DONNAN:
And they would say, "Well, let me see."

01:20:59.522 --> 01:21:02.690
And so he's stumbling around,
and it was pitiful.

01:21:02.775 --> 01:21:06.486
lt was so insulting. l just felt so bad for him.

01:21:06.570 --> 01:21:08.321
And l was totally powerless.

01:21:08.405 --> 01:21:09.906
There's nothing you can do.

01:21:09.990 --> 01:21:12.742
PETER: She was not next to tears.

01:21:12.826 --> 01:21:14.327
She was way past that.

01:21:15.454 --> 01:21:17.205
l just. . . lt broke my heart.

01:21:18.499 --> 01:21:23.878
DONNAN: There was finally a time
when the man said, "Get out of here."

01:21:23.963 --> 01:21:25.880
So l drove around him,

01:21:25.965 --> 01:21:28.883
and then l couldn't see him anymore.

01:21:28.968 --> 01:21:31.302
And the only choice you have
is to go out the driveway

01:21:31.387 --> 01:21:35.139
and turn on the desolate road

01:21:35.224 --> 01:21:38.142
and drive 1 0 hours,

01:21:38.227 --> 01:21:40.478
you know, home.

01:21:40.563 --> 01:21:44.232
l think l screamed for about 1 0 minutes,

01:21:44.316 --> 01:21:45.900
driving.

01:21:45.985 --> 01:21:49.404
lt was wild. l didn't have any other choice.

01:21:49.488 --> 01:21:52.073
l had to get it out. lt was hard.

01:21:54.326 --> 01:21:56.828
lt was the hardest thing l ever did.

01:21:56.912 --> 01:21:58.246
Ever.

01:21:58.330 --> 01:22:01.874
The guard who was there
filling out the paperwork

01:22:01.959 --> 01:22:03.376
said, "Have you seen this?"

01:22:03.460 --> 01:22:05.128
And l said, "Seen what?" And he said,

01:22:05.212 --> 01:22:08.131
"Come here."
And he looked at the piece of paper,

01:22:08.215 --> 01:22:13.511
and it said, "Reason for incarceration,
failure to fill out forms."

01:22:13.804 --> 01:22:17.056
And he said, "Man, you must have
really pissed somebody off."

01:22:59.224 --> 01:23:01.976
Prison was very surreal.

01:23:02.061 --> 01:23:03.186
Um...

01:23:04.104 --> 01:23:09.484
The thing about prison
is not the fact that you're in prison,

01:23:09.568 --> 01:23:13.613
so much as you are kept
from your family and your friends.

01:23:13.697 --> 01:23:15.490
After a couple of weeks,

01:23:15.574 --> 01:23:18.034
l said, "l have an idea.

01:23:18.118 --> 01:23:22.121
"They used to have a little thing here
that they called Saturday morning lectures

01:23:22.206 --> 01:23:23.414
"and people who would give lectures.

01:23:23.499 --> 01:23:26.668
"They aren't doing that anymore.
l'd like to start that up again.

01:23:26.752 --> 01:23:28.586
"We've got lawyers. We've got doctors.

01:23:28.671 --> 01:23:30.672
"We've got physical therapists.
We've got realtors.

01:23:30.756 --> 01:23:32.382
"We've got drug dealers, too,
and counterfeiters

01:23:32.466 --> 01:23:34.008
"and all kinds of things like that,

01:23:34.093 --> 01:23:36.010
"but these drug dealers,

01:23:36.095 --> 01:23:39.389
"who've never had
a different job in their life,

01:23:39.473 --> 01:23:41.557
"l think it would be helpful

01:23:41.642 --> 01:23:43.685
"for them to learn
how to do these other things."

01:23:43.769 --> 01:23:45.228
We went down there.
You have to get clearance,

01:23:45.312 --> 01:23:48.022
and, you know, it's like
you're surrounded by all these. . .

01:23:48.107 --> 01:23:51.484
You know, he's got a uniform with the,
you know, numbers on it and stuff.

01:23:51.568 --> 01:23:54.195
He says, "Well, l'm leading the debate club,

01:23:54.279 --> 01:23:56.698
"and l have a paleontological club
that l'm working on.

01:23:56.782 --> 01:23:59.534
"They have some great, you know,
minerals around here."

01:23:59.618 --> 01:24:03.037
He was teaching the prisoners
how to, you know, do paleontology

01:24:03.122 --> 01:24:04.372
right there on the prison grounds.

01:24:04.456 --> 01:24:06.207
That's what it's like with Pete.

01:24:06.291 --> 01:24:08.376
l mean, he will find the beauty
in everything around him.

01:24:08.460 --> 01:24:11.295
DONNAN: The other inmates loved him,

01:24:11.380 --> 01:24:13.715
and it was very clear
that they protected him.

01:24:13.799 --> 01:24:17.468
Not like in a movie,
where they beat people up for him,

01:24:17.553 --> 01:24:19.721
but just they took care of him in some way,

01:24:19.805 --> 01:24:22.557
like they just felt a proprietary interest

01:24:22.641 --> 01:24:25.435
for him, like he was special,

01:24:25.519 --> 01:24:29.522
and it was very sweet to see
that they saw who he was.

01:24:52.796 --> 01:24:54.297
PETER: When finally the day came,

01:24:54.381 --> 01:24:58.009
l'm riding all night long
on this bus that stops every five minutes.

01:24:58.093 --> 01:24:59.260
DONNAN: l couldn't go pick up Pete.

01:24:59.344 --> 01:25:01.304
He had to get on a bus, a public bus.

01:25:01.388 --> 01:25:03.306
PETER:
'Cause you're still technically in prison.

01:25:03.390 --> 01:25:05.099
l'm still serving my sentence.

01:25:05.184 --> 01:25:07.018
Riding in the bus,

01:25:07.102 --> 01:25:10.021
even though it was driving all night long,

01:25:10.105 --> 01:25:11.439
was great.

01:25:15.444 --> 01:25:20.740
lt was my first taste of freedom
for 1 8 months, where l'm out of this prison.

01:25:21.700 --> 01:25:26.788
And finally, in the morning of
the next day, I arrive in Rapid City.

01:25:26.872 --> 01:25:29.707
ZENKER: Kristin was standing there,
and she just told everybody,

01:25:29.792 --> 01:25:33.461
"Stand back because
this is gonna take some time."

01:25:33.545 --> 01:25:36.506
lt was great. lt was great. He was back home.

01:25:36.590 --> 01:25:40.051
l mean, he was under house arrest,
but he was back home. We could see him.

01:25:40.135 --> 01:25:42.512
PETER: Eventually l'm released
from the halfway house

01:25:42.596 --> 01:25:45.556
to home confinement,
where l can only go from home to work,

01:25:45.641 --> 01:25:47.600
so l get to walk across
the alley every morning

01:25:47.684 --> 01:25:50.186
and across the alley
back home at night, and that's it.

01:25:51.772 --> 01:25:55.191
NEAL: When Pete got out of prison,
he was not the person he was when he left.

01:25:55.275 --> 01:25:59.195
He was very reclusive.
He was very withdrawn.

01:25:59.279 --> 01:26:01.656
DONNAN: He had to reorient

01:26:01.740 --> 01:26:04.575
to normal interactions with people.

01:26:04.743 --> 01:26:08.454
The lnstitute was not the happy place
that it sometimes is.

01:26:08.539 --> 01:26:11.707
Things were a little gloomier. We didn't. . .

01:26:11.792 --> 01:26:16.337
Still didn't know how the long-term
effects of this would leave us.

01:26:16.421 --> 01:26:18.840
We just had to keep plugging along

01:26:18.924 --> 01:26:21.384
and try to cope as well as we could.

